(526, 'home', 'The starting point for a line, page, document, or website.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(527, 'home directory', 'A location in an organizational structure that contains the personal files of a given user of the system.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(528, 'homepage', 'The main page in a website; the page set to open in a web browser when it is loaded.', 'Example 1: Visit our homepage and click on "Products" for information about prices and availability.\r\n\r\nExample 2: To set the Kamusi Project as your homepage in Firefox, go to Tools/Options/Main, type http://kamusiproject.org/ into the input box, and click OK.', 'n', '6', 1, 'core'),
(529, 'host', 'A computer connected to the Internet.', 'In computer networking, a network host, Internet host or host is a computer connected to the Internet. A network host can host information as well as client and/or server software.\r\n\r\nEvery Internet host has a unique IP address, including a host address part. The host address is assigned either manually by the computer administrator, or automatically at start-up by means of the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).\r\n\r\nEvery host is a network node (i.e. a network device), but every node is not a host. Network nodes such as modems and network switches are not assigned host addresses, and are not considered as hosts. Devices such as network printers and hardware routers are assigned IP host addresses, but since they are not general-purpose computers, they are sometimes not considered as hosts in the literature.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(530, 'hostname', 'The unique identifier by which any device attached to a network is known.', 'A hostname (occasionally also, a sitename) is the unique name by which a network-attached device (which could consist of a computer, file server, network storage device, fax machine, copier, cable modem, etc.) is known on a network. The hostname is used to identify a particular host in various forms of electronic communication such as the World Wide Web, e-mail or Usenet.\r\n\r\nOn the Internet, the terms "hostname" and "domain name" are often used interchangeably, but there are subtle technical differences between them.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(531, 'hotkey', 'A button or set of buttons on an input device that is programmed to perform a predefined function.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(532, 'hotspot', 'An area in which Internet services can be accessed through a wireless Wi-Fi signal.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(533, 'hue', 'The shade, tint, or gradation of a color.', 'Hue is one of the main properties of a color described with names such as "red", "yellow", etc. The two other main properties are lightness and colorfulness. Hue is also one of the three dimensions in some colorspaces along with saturation, and brightness.\r\n\r\nUsually, colors with the same hue are distinguished with adjectives referring to their lightness and/or chroma, such as with "light blue", "pastel blue", "vivid blue".', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(534, 'hyperlink', 'A connection from one file or web page to another.', 'In computing, a hyperlink is a reference, link, or navigation element in a document to another place, such as another section of the same document or to another document that may be on or part of a (different) domain. To insert a hyperlink to another place is often simply called to "link". Hypertext (meaning "more than just" text) is a form of text typically published on websites that provides a richer functionality than simple text documents by enabling the reader to explore interesting links to other web pages linked to specific words or images within the page.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(535, 'hypertext', 'A method of labeling a portion of a document so that clicking on it will open a link to another location, document, or file.', 'Hypertext most often refers to text on a computer that will lead the user to other, related information on demand. Hypertext allows a form of user interface, which overcomes some of the limitations of written text. Rather than remaining static like traditional text, hypertext makes possible a dynamic organization of information through links and connections (called hyperlinks). Hypertext can be designed to perform various tasks; for instance when a user "clicks" on it or "hovers" over it, a bubble with a word definition may appear, a web page on a related subject may load, a video clip may run, or an application may open.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(536, 'hyphenate', 'Divide or connect words with a short dash.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(537, 'hyphenation', 'The act or process of dividing or joining words with a short dash.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(538, 'icon', 'A small picture used to represent a program, file, person, company, etc.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(539, 'identifier', 'An unambiguous reference to a resource within a given context.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(540, 'identity', 'The set of characteristics by which a person or thing is recognizable or known.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(541, 'idle', 'Not in active use.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
