(1218, 'WAN (Wide Area Network)', 'A group of computers connected over a broad distance.', 'Wide Area Network (WAN) is a computer network that covers a broad area (i.e., any network whose communications links cross metropolitan, regional, or national boundaries [1]). Less formally, a WAN is a network that uses routers and public communications links [1]. Contrast with personal area networks (PANs), local area networks (LANs), campus area networks (CANs), or metropolitan area networks (MANs) which are usually limited to a room, building, campus or specific metropolitan area (e.g., a city) respectively. The largest and most well-known example of a WAN is the Internet.\r\n\r\nWANs are used to connect LANs and other types of networks together, so that users and computers in one location can communicate with users and computers in other locations. Many WANs are built for one particular organization and are private. Others, built by Internet service providers, provide connections from an organization''s LAN to the Internet.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1219, 'warn', 'Make aware of impending danger.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1220, 'warning', 'A precautionary statement or notice of impending danger.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1221, 'watch', 'Observe over a period of time.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1222, 'watermark', 'A translucent design embedded into digital material to identify or protect content.', 'A watermark is a recognizable image or pattern in paper that appears as various shades of lightness/darkness when viewed by transmitted light (or when viewed by reflected light, atop a dark background), caused by thickness variations in the paper. There are two main types of watermark, the Dandy Roll process, and the more complex Cylinder Mould process. A watermark is very useful in the examination of paper because it can be used for dating, identifying sizes, mill trademarks and locations, and the quality of a paper.\r\n\r\nWatermarks vary greatly in their visibility; while some are obvious on casual inspection, others require some study to pick out. Various aids have been developed, such as watermark fluid that wets the paper without damaging it. Encoding an identifying code into digitized music, video, picture, or other file is known as a digital watermark.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1343, 'embedded', 'Inserted inside a larger document or file.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1223, 'web', 'A system of interlinked hypertext documents.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1342, 'drag and drop', 'Move something from one location to another by selecting it, holding down a mouse button, moving the mouse to the new location, and releasing the mouse button.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1224, 'web layout', 'The arrangement of the elements of a document for display on the Internet.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1225, 'web page', 'A document designed for viewing online in a browser.', 'A web page or webpage is a resource of information that is suitable for the World Wide Web and can be accessed through a web browser. This information is usually in HTML or XHTML format, and may provide navigation to other web pages via hypertext links.\r\n\r\nWeb pages may be retrieved from a local computer or from a remote web server. The web server may restrict access only to a private network, e.g. a corporate intranet, or it may publish pages on the World Wide Web. Web pages are requested and served from web servers using Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1226, 'website', 'A collection of interlinked documents made available on the Internet through a common homepage.', 'A website is a collection of Web pages, images, videos or other digital assets that is hosted on one or more web servers, usually accessible via the Internet.\r\n\r\nA Web page is a document, typically written in (X)HTML, that is almost always accessible via HTTP, a protocol that transfers information from the Web server to display in the user''s Web browser.\r\n\r\nAll publicly accessible websites are seen collectively as constituting the "World Wide Web".\r\n\r\nThe pages of a website can usually be accessed from a common root URL called the homepage, and usually reside on the same physical server. The URLs of the pages organize them into a hierarchy, although the hyperlinks between them control how the reader perceives the overall structure and how the traffic flows between the different parts of the site.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1227, 'webcast', 'A media file distributed over the Internet using streaming media technology.', 'Essentially, webcasting is â€œbroadcastingâ€ over the Internet.  A webcast may either be distributed live or on demand. ', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1228, 'webmail', 'A way of accessing email online using a browser.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1229, 'webmaster', 'The person responsible for designing, developing, marketing, or maintaining a website.', 'Webmasters are practitioners of web communication. Typically, they are generalists with HTML expertise who manage all aspects of Web operations. Webmasters typically know scripting languages such as PHP, Perl and Javascript.\r\n\r\nOn larger sites, the webmaster will act as a coordinator and overseer to the activities of other people working on the site and is usually an employee of the owner of the website, hence webmaster can also be listed as an occupation. If the webmaster is hired by a larger website, or promoted to the position, they could do things from web design, to project management, or employee supervision.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1341, 'down ', 'At a lower place or position. ', '', 'adv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1230, 'widget', 'A small program designed to do one specific task.', 'A web widget is a portable chunk of code that can be installed and executed within any separate HTML-based web page by an end user without requiring additional compilation. They are derived from the idea of code reuse. Other terms used to describe web widgets include: gadget, badge, module, webjit, capsule, snippet, mini and flake. Web widgets usually but not always use DHTML, JavaScript, or Adobe Flash.\r\n\r\nWidgets often take the form of on-screen tools (clocks, event countdowns, auction-tickers, stock market tickers, flight arrival information, daily weather etc).', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1340, 'documentation', 'A collection of information that describes how to use a product.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1231, 'width', 'The measurement of the dimensions of something from side to side.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1232, 'window', 'A rectangular area on a computer screen containing some kind of user interface.', '', 'n', '8', 2, 'core'),
(1339, 'displayed', 'Shown or made visible.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1233, 'wizard', 'A user interface that uses a series of dialog boxes to complete a task.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1338, 'digital camera', 'A photographic device that records pictures electronically rather than on film.', '', 'n', '9;11;12', 2, 'core'),
(1234, 'word count', 'The number of words a document contains.', '', 'n', '4', 1, 'core'),
(1235, 'word processor', 'A computer application used for the production (including composition, editing, formatting, and possibly printing) of any sort of printable material.', '', 'n', '4', 1, 'core'),
(1236, 'workbook', 'A spreadsheet file that may contain numerous worksheets.', 'In the Microsoft spreadsheet program Excel, a single document is known as a "workbook" and by default each workbook contains three arrays or "worksheets." One advantage of such programs is that they can contain formulas so that if one cell value is changed, the entire document is automatically updated, based on those formulas. Analysts, investors, and accountants track a company''s financial statements, balance sheets, and other data on worksheets. Worksheets can be made with Microsoft Office Excel and other formula based software. More sophisticated database programs may display data from many tables as a "view."', 'n', '4', 1, 'core'),
(1337, 'dial-up ', 'Using a telephone line and a modem to connect to a network.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1237, 'workgroup', 'A peer-to-peer computer network.', '', 'n', '9', 1, 'core'),
(1336, 'dial tone', 'A sound emitted by a land-line telephone when the phone is connected to the network and enabled to make a call.', 'A dial tone (known in the British Isles as a dialling tone) is a telephony signal used to indicate that the telephone exchange is working, has recognized an off-hook, and is ready to accept a call. The tone stops when the first numeral is dialed.', 'n', '', 1, 'core');
INSERT INTO `gm_en` (`en_id`, `en_word`, `en_def`, `en_comment`, `en_syn_group`, `en_tag`, `en_status`, `en_type`) VALUES
(1238, 'worksheet', 'A data file made up of rows and columns.', 'In the Microsoft spreadsheet program Excel, a single document is known as a "workbook" and by default each workbook contains three arrays or "worksheets." One advantage of such programs is that they can contain formulas so that if one cell value is changed, the entire document is automatically updated, based on those formulas. Analysts, investors, and accountants track a company''s financial statements, balance sheets, and other data on worksheets. Worksheets can be made with Microsoft Office Excel and other formula based software. More sophisticated database programs may display data from many tables as a "view."', 'n', '4', 1, 'core'),
(1335, 'dial out ', 'Call a telephone number at an external location.', '', 'iv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1334, 'dial', 'Input telephone number to call.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1239, 'wrap', 'Have text that reaches the edge of the window automatically move to the next line.', '', 'tv', '4', 1, 'core'),
(1333, 'diagnostics', 'Test or process used to determine the source of a problem.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1240, 'write protected', 'Secured with a physical mechanism that prevents modification or erasure of data.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1332, 'device manager', 'A tool in Windows that allows users to control equipment attached to the computer.', 'The Device Manager is a Control Panel applet in Microsoft Windows operating systems. It allows users to view and control the hardware attached to the computer. When a piece of hardware is not working, the offending hardware is highlighted for the user to deal with. The list of hardware can be sorted by various criteria.\r\n\r\nFor each device, users can:\r\n\r\n    * Supply device drivers for the hardware\r\n    * Enable or disable devices\r\n    * Tell Windows to ignore malfunctioning devices\r\n    * View other technical properties\r\n', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1331, 'detect', 'Look to see if something is present.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1330, 'delimiter', 'A character or sequence of characters used to separate elements within a file.', 'A delimiter is one or more characters  that separates text strings. Common delimiters are commas (,), semicolon  (;), quotes ( ", '' ), braces ({}), pipes(|), or slashes ( / \\ ).  When a program stores a lot of data it may use a delimiter to separate each of the data values. For example, "john||doe" has two pipe characters as its separator, the program could easily distinguish between a first and last name.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1329, 'deletion', 'An item that has been or will be removed or erased.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1241, 'zone', 'Area or region.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1242, 'zoom', 'Change the viewing size of images or text.', '', 'iv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1243, 'zoom in', 'Increase the viewing size of images or text.', '', 'iv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1244, 'zoom out', 'Decrease the viewing size of images or text.', '', 'iv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1328, 'deleting', 'Removing or erasing.', '', 'part', '', 1, 'core'),
(1245, 'partition', 'The part of a hard disk that is dedicated to a particular operating system or application and accessed as a single unit.', 'Disk partitioning is the creation of separate divisions of a hard disk drive using partition editors. Once a disk is divided into several partitions, directories and files of different categories may be stored in different partitions. More partitions provide more control but too many may become cumbersome. The way space management, access permissions and directory searching are implemented depends upon the type of file system installed on a partition. Careful consideration of the size of the partition is necessary as the ability to change the size depends on the file system installed on the partition.\r\n\r\nPurposes for partitioning:\r\n\r\n    * Separation of the operating system files from user files\r\n\r\n    * Having an area for operating system virtual memory swapping/paging\r\n\r\n    * Keeping frequently used programs and data near each other.\r\n\r\n    * Having cache and log files separate from other files. These can change size dynamically and rapidly, potentially making a file system full.\r\n\r\n    * Use of multi booting setups, which allow users to have more than one operating system on a single computer. For example, one could install Linux, Mac OS X, Microsoft Windows or others on different partitions of the same hard disk and have a choice of booting into any operating system (supported by the hardware) at power-up.\r\n\r\n    * Protecting or isolating files, to make it easier to recover a corrupted file system or operating system installation. If one partition is corrupted, none of the other file systems are affected, and the drive''s data may still be salvageable. Having a separate partition for read-only data also reduces the chances of the file system on this partition becoming corrupted.\r\n\r\n    * Raising overall computer performance on systems where smaller file systems are more efficient. For instance, large hard drives with only one NTFS file system typically have a very large sequentially-accessed Master File Table (MFT) and it generally takes more time to read this MFT than the smaller MFTs of smaller partitions.\r\n', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1246, 'partition', 'Divide something into sections.', '', 'tv', '9', 1, 'core'),
(1247, 'channel (hardware)', 'A communications path between two computers or devices.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1327, 'del / delete key', 'Keyboard button to remove or erase something.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1248, 'acronym', 'Abbreviation that is formed using the initial components in a phrase or name.', 'Example: URL is the acronym for Uniform Resource Locator.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1326, 'default value', 'The original configuration of an option in a program or device.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1249, 'UPS', 'A battery back-up that provides domestic emergency power for computer equipment during blackouts of the public power supply.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1325, 'dedicated', 'Assigned to a specific user or purpose.', 'Example: For 530 USD/month, they get a dedicated international bandwidth of 175/50 Kbps with a volume restriction of 3 GB/month.', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1324, 'decode', 'Convert from an encrypted or compressed form to a form that can be read or used.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1323, 'decision', 'The choice of one from among a number of alternatives.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1322, 'customized', 'Modified according to individual preferences.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1321, 'cross-post ', 'Submit the same comment to multiple blogs or websites.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1320, 'cross-posting', 'Submitting the same comment to multiple blogs or websites.', '', 'part', '', 1, 'core'),
(1319, 'credentials', 'Documentation attesting to the truth of certain stated facts.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1318, 'country code', 'A two letter abbreviation used to distinguish a nation in postal or electronic communications; a set of numbers used to distinguish a nation for international dialing.', 'Example 1: The country code to send a letter to Tanzania is TZ.\r\n\r\nExample 2: The country code to call Tanzania is 255.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1317, 'corrupt', 'Damage data in some way.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1316, 'corrupted', 'Containing data that has been damaged in some way.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1315, 'connection failure', 'Communication link not established.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1314, 'configuration file', 'User preferences and set-up instructions for software or hardware.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1250, 'serif', 'A short horizontal line or hook added to the tops and bottoms of characters in many typefaces.', 'In typography, serifs are semi-structural details on the ends of some of the strokes that make up letters and symbols. A typeface that has serifs is called a serif typeface (or seriffed typeface). A typeface without serifs is called sans-serif, from the French sans, meaning â€œwithoutâ€.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1251, 'sans serif', 'A typeface that does not have small lines or curves at the end of strokes.', 'In typography, a sans-serif or sans serif typeface is one that does not have the small features called "serifs" at the end of strokes. The term comes from the French word sans, meaning "without".\r\n\r\nIn print, sans-serif fonts are more typically used for headlines than for body text. The conventional wisdom is serifs help guide the eye along the lines in large blocks of text.\r\n\r\nSans-serif fonts have become the de facto standard for body text on-screen, especially online. It has been suggested this is because the small size of the font causes serif fonts to appear excessively cluttered on the screen. This is also true of typography on mobile screens, though it is less commonly used in television screens.', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1252, 'optimized', 'Best or most desirable.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1253, 'monochrome', 'Using only gradations of a single color.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1313, 'com port ', 'A socket on a computer used for connecting cables to other devices.', 'com port is short for "communications port".', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1254, 'mixer', 'A device that combines two or more electronic signals into one composite output signal.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1255, 'infrared', 'Beam used for short-ranged wireless communication, similar to light but having a higher wavelength.', 'Electromagnetic radiation of a wavelength longer than visible light, but shorter than microwave radiation, having a wavelength between 700 nm and 1 mm.', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1256, 'hand-held', 'Of a size that can comfortably be carried and used in an adult hand.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1312, 'common', 'Occurring or happening regularly or frequently.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1257, 'cryptography', 'The practice of hiding information through codes.', '', 'n', '8', 1, 'core'),
(1311, 'column span', 'Have cells in a table spread over multiple vertical lines of data.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1258, 'sharpness', 'An imageâ€™s degree of clarity in terms of focus and contrast.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1259, 'soften', 'Reduce the focus or intensity.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1310, 'color resolution', 'The amount of data about hue, saturation, and brightness that is displayed in a given area.', 'Resolution refers to the number of pixels in an image. The more pixels, the higher the resolution. The higher the resolution, the better the picture.  So, high color resolution means that the colors in an image or display will appear with a lot of detail. ', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1309, 'colon', 'The punctuation mark ":" introducing a quotation, definition, or a series of items.', 'As with many other punctuation marks, the usage of colon varies among languages and, for a given language, among historical periods. As a rule, however, a colon informs the reader what follows proves and explains, or simply enumerates elements of what is referred to before.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1308, 'client', 'An application or system that accesses a remote service on another computer system, known as a server, by way of a network.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1307, 'cipher', 'Something written in a secret code.', 'In cryptography, a cipher (or cypher) is an algorithm for performing encryption and decryption â€” a series of well-defined steps that can be followed as a procedure. An alternative term is encipherment. In non-technical usage, a â€œcipherâ€ is the same thing as a â€œcodeâ€; however, the concepts are distinct in cryptography. In classical cryptography, ciphers were distinguished from codes. Codes operated by substituting according to a large codebook which linked a random string of characters or numbers to a word or phrase. For example, â€œUQJHSEâ€ could be the code for â€œProceed to the following coordinatesâ€. When using a cipher the original information is known as plaintext, and the encrypted form as ciphertext. The ciphertext message contains all the information of the plaintext message, but is not in a format readable by a human or computer without the proper mechanism to decrypt it; it should resemble random gibberish to those not intended to read it.\r\n\r\nThe operation of a cipher usually depends on a piece of auxiliary information, called a key or, in traditional NSA parlance, a cryptovariable. The encrypting procedure is varied depending on the key, which changes the detailed operation of the algorithm. A key must be selected before using a cipher to encrypt a message. Without knowledge of the key, it should be difficult, if not nearly impossible, to decrypt the resulting cipher into readable plaintext.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1306, 'finder', 'The graphical representation of a computer''s file system for Apple Macintosh operating systems.', 'The Finder is the default application program used on the Mac OS and Mac OS X operating systems that is responsible for the overall user-management of files, disks, network volumes and the launching of other applications. As such the Finder acts like the shell on other operating systems, but using a graphical user interface, and is described in its ''About'' window as The Macintosh Desktop Experience. It was introduced with the very first Macintosh computer, and also existed as part of GS/OS on the Apple IIGS. It underwent a complete rewrite with Apple''s switch to a UNIX-based OS in Mac OS X.\r\n\r\nThe Finder is the first program a user interacts with after booting a Mac (and potentially logging in), and as such it is responsible for the general look and feel of the machine. One should be careful to distinguish this from the actual GUI of the machine, which is really provided by particular services within the operating system (eg, WindowServer). The Finder is just another application, albeit the default one. It can even be closed if the user knows how, although it is difficult to replace completely. In particular, many software installers quit the Finder, substituting their own interface to manipulate the System, including Apple''s own System installation programs. One could compare it to Windows Explorer in Microsoft Windows, the Tracker in BeOS, Nautilus in GNOME, and Dolphin or the file management aspect of Konqueror in KDE.\r\n\r\nThe Finder maintains a view of the file system that is rendered using the desktop metaphor - that is, the files and folders are represented as appropriate icons, volumes are displayed on the desktop, and there is a trash can (on the Dock in OS X, on the desktop in previous versions) to which files can be dragged to mark them for deletion.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1305, 'chime', 'A sound used to call attention to a certain condition.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1304, 'check for', 'Look to see if something exists or a condition has been met.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1303, 'chat group', 'A site on the internet where a number of users can communicate in real time about a specific topic.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1260, 'tile', 'Arrange items on a screen in rectangular units of equal size.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1261, 'rate', 'Offer an opinion about quality or value.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1302, 'change', 'Make something different.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1301, 'CD / compact disk', 'A small disc for optical storage of digital data, especially used for distributing music.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1300, 'capture ', 'Record an image with a digital device, either by taking a picture with a digital camera, scanning, or converting from analog format.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1299, 'call out', 'A graphic device or piece of text pointing attention to a larger image or section of text.', 'A pull quote (also known as a lift-out quote or a call-out) is a quotation or edited excerpt from an article that is placed in a larger typeface on the same page, serving to lead readers into an article and to highlight a key topic. The term is principally used in journalism and publishing. Some publications choose not to align the pull quote with the columns on a page; in that case, it cuts into two or more columns to reduce the linearity of a page. Placement of a pull quote on a page is usually defined in a publication''s own style manual.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1262, 'webcam', 'A video camera whose output may be viewed in real time over a network, especially over the Internet.', 'Webcams are video capturing devices connected to computers or computer networks, often using USB or, if they connect to networks, ethernet or Wi-Fi. They are well-known for their low manufacturing costs and flexible applications.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1263, 'peer', 'A computer that acts as both a client and a server in a local network.', 'A Peer to Peer (or P2P) computer network uses diverse connectivity between participants in a network and the cumulative bandwidth of network participants rather than conventional centralized resources where a relatively low number of servers provide the core value to a service or application. P2P networks are typically used for connecting nodes via largely ad hoc connections. Such networks are useful for many purposes. Sharing content files (see file sharing) containing audio, video, data or anything in digital format is very common, and realtime data, such as telephony traffic, is also passed using P2P technology.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1298, 'bulleted list', 'A set of items arranged in a sequence, with each separate item identified by the typographical bullet symbol, that is â€¢, or with another symbol other than numbers.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1297, 'bounced', 'Returned without being delivered to the intended recipient.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1296, 'blocked', 'Access prevented.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1264, 'fade in', 'A type of transition used in visual media, in which the a black background is gradually filled with a visual image; a type of transition used in audio media, in which the volume is gradually increased.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1265, 'fade out', 'A type of transition used in visual media, in which a visual image is gradually replaced with a black background; a type of transition used in audio media, in which the volume is gradually decreased to silence.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1295, 'bitmap', 'A grid of pixels or printed dots generated by computer to represent images.', 'A bitmap is a graphics file format. It is the basic and default picture file type from the Microsoft Paint program. There is no compression of the image therefore no loss of image clarity and as a result, bitmap (.bmp) files tend to be much larger in size than compressed formats such as jpeg.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1294, 'binary ', 'The system by which combinations of 0s and 1s are used to represent any type of data stored on a computer.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1293, 'beta', 'A version of an application that is made available prior to the official release for the purposes of testing.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1292, 'baud', 'The unit of measurement of data transmission speed over a communications circuit.', 'One baud is approximately equal to one "bit per second" (BPS).  A 56K modem has a speed of 56,000 baud or 56,000 BPS.', 'n', '9', 1, 'core'),
(1266, 'tweak', 'Make very small adjustments.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1291, 'bandwidth', 'A measure of the amount or speed of data transmission.', '', 'n', '9', 2, 'core'),
(1290, 'backslash', 'The punctuation mark \\', 'The backslash ( \\ ) is a typographical mark (glyph) used chiefly in computing.  It is sometimes used to indicate the beginning and ending of an area of words being marked for correction.\r\n\r\nOn Unix systems, and in many programming languages such as C and Perl, the backslash is used to indicate that the character following it should be treated specially. \r\n\r\nIn DOS and Microsoft Windows, either the backslash or slash can be used as the delimiter between directories and filenames in path expressions. This is in contrast to Unix paths and Internet URLs (web addresses), which only use the forward slash. ', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1267, 'tips and tricks', 'Useful information and techniques that can improve a user''s experience.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1289, 'background color', 'A set of values for hue, saturation, and brightness displayed on a website or computer desktop behind the visible content.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1288, 'back button', 'A browser feature used to return to the previous web page.', 'Used to visit the previous page that referred you to the page you are currently located at. This button is likely going to be the button you use the most while browsing on the Internet and is usually a large arrow pointing to the left.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1287, 'autocorrect', 'A software function that corrects common spelling or typing errors immediately after they are input.', 'Text replacement, Replace as you type or AutoCorrect is a software function commonly found in word processors such as Microsoft Word. Its principal purpose is to correct common spelling or typing errors, saving time for the user. It is also used to automatically format text or insert special characters by recognising particular character usage, saving the user from having to use more tedious functions.\r\n\r\nAdditional options include recognising words with two initial capital letters (e.g. "EXample") and correcting them, capitalising the first letters of sentences, and correcting accidental use of caps lock (e.g. eXAMPLE).\r\n\r\nThe replacement list for text replacement can also be modified by the user, allowing the user to use shortcuts. If, for example, the user is writing an essay on the industrial revolution, a replacement key can be set up to replace the ''word'' "ir" with "industrial revolution", saving the user time whenever he wants to type it.\r\n\r\nExamples: \r\nInput 	Output\r\nyuor  ||  your\r\n(r)  ||  Â®\r\naboutit  ||  about it\r\nwhere;s  ||  where''s\r\n*bold* 	||  bold\r\n_italic_  ||  italic', 'tv', '4', 1, 'core'),
(1268, 'camcorder', 'A video camera, i.e., a device that records continuous pictures.', 'A camcorder is a portable consumer electronics device for recording video and audio using a built-in recorder unit. The camcorder contains both a video camera and a video recorder in one unit, hence its compound name.', 'n', '11', 1, 'core'),
(1269, 'USB Stick, Memory Stick', 'Small portable device to store and transport files.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1286, 'autocomplete', 'Fill in a text input area with data that has been typed or stored previously.', 'Autocomplete is a feature provided by many source code text editors, word processors, and web browsers. Autocomplete involves the program predicting a word or phrase that the user wants to type in without the user actually typing it in completely. This feature is effective when it is easy to predict the word being typed based on those already typed, such as when there are a limited number of possible or commonly used words (as is the case with email programs, web browsers, or command line interpreters), or when editing text written in a highly-structured, easy-to-predict language (as in source code editors). Autocomplete speeds up human-computer interactions in environments to which it is well suited.', 'tv', '4;6', 2, 'core'),
(1285, 'author', 'Writer or creator.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1284, 'at', 'In or very near a particular location. ', 'The word "at" is used within email addresses as the spoken form of the symbol @.  For example, the email address somebody@kamusiproject.org is read: "somebody AT kamusiproject dot org"', 'prep', '', 1, 'core'),
(1283, 'assigned', 'Have a value set.', 'In computer science the assignment statement sets or re-sets the value stored in the storage location(s) denoted by a variable name. In most imperative computer programming languages the assignment statement is one of the basic statements.\r\n\r\nThe assignment statement often allows that the same variable name to contain different values at different times during program execution.', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1282, 'ASCII ', 'A set of 128 alphanumeric and special control characters based on the English alphabet.', 'American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII), pronounced /ËˆÃ¦ski/ is a character encoding based on the English alphabet. ASCII codes represent text in computers, communications equipment, and other devices that work with text. Most modern character encodingsâ€”which support many more characters than did the originalâ€”have a historical basis in ASCII.\r\n\r\nASCII includes definitions for 128 characters: 33 are non-printing, mostly obsolete control characters that affect how text is processed; 94 are printable characters, and the space is considered an invisible graphic. The ASCII character encoding is the most commonly used character set on the Internet.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1281, 'artificial intelligence / AI', 'The reproduction or mimicking of human-level thought in computers.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1280, 'anonymity', 'A condition in which an individual''s true identity is unknown.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1270, 'bot', 'A computer program that does automated tasks.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1279, 'ampersand', 'The symbol "&"', 'An ampersand (&), also commonly called an " ''and'' sign," is a logogram representing the conjunction "and".\r\n\r\nThe ampersand is also used in many computer languages to indicate a variety of special entities.  For example, in HTML, ''&copy;'' is the code to tell a web browser to print the Â© (copyright symbol).', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1278, 'alt ', 'A key on a keyboard that that provides alternate functions when pressed at the same time as other keys.', '', 'n', '9', 1, 'core'),
(1271, 'printer-friendly', 'Webpage display format that enables the printing of the page correctly on standard-size paper.', '[From About.com]\r\n\r\nMany Web designers feel that if a Web page is written for the Web, that''s where it should be read. But some Web pages can be difficult to read online, either because of the ads and flashing blinking images, or because they are so long that it''s easier to read them in print. For how to articles, it''s easier to have the article printed out to follow along with, perhaps writing notes or checking off the steps as they are completed.\r\n\r\nWhat Makes a Printer-Friendly Page Printer-Friendly?\r\n\r\nThere are some disagreements about how to write a printer-friendly page. Some people feel that only the article content and title (with perhaps a by-line) should be included on the page. Other developers just remove the side and top navigation or replace them with text links at the bottom of the article. Some sites remove advertising, other sites remove some advertising, and still others leave all of the advertising intact. ', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1434, 'aborted', 'Stopped without being completed successfully.', 'Example: The file transfer was aborted because the connection was lost. Try again?', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1435, 'aborting', 'Stopping an action without completing it successfully.', 'Example: Aborting file transfer.', '', '', 1, 'core'),
(1436, 'accept all', 'Approve an entire list of items', 'Example: When someone else edits your document using the "Track Changes" feature, you can choose "Accept All Changes" to agree to all of their edits.', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1437, 'accepted', 'Be agreed to.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1438, 'access denied', 'Not permitted to view or retrieve an existing file.', 'Message displayed when unable to obtain access to a location that you have not been granted the proper access rights or do not have permission to access. ', '', '', 1, 'core'),
(1439, 'access permissions', 'Rights that an administrator can grant or deny for a user to view, read or write a particular file or directory.', 'If the account does not have the proper access permissions, you may be unable to view, read or write to a certain directory or file. When this occurs, you would likely receive the access denied error. ', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1440, 'accessed', 'Successfully connected with a website, database, or hard-drive.', 'Example: Website accessed on January 12', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1441, 'account information', 'Personal user data.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1442, 'account name', 'A unique word or phrase that a user chooses to use as identification.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1443, 'account settings', 'Options that can be configured for a particular user on a website.', '', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1444, 'activated', 'Started; turned on.', '', 'adj', '', 1, 'core'),
(1445, 'activating', 'Starting; turning on.', '', 'part', '', 1, 'core'),
(1446, 'activation', 'A secure process of enabling commercial software to function.', 'Example: Activation of this software requires you to enter the 25 digit product key that came with your Microsoft product.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1447, 'active document', 'The file on a computer that is currently selected to receive input.', 'Example: Printing page 4 of the active document', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1448, 'active link', 'A text element on a web page that has been selected or clicked for connection to another web page.', 'Example: After you click on the title of the article you want to read, the link may be shown in red until you are transferred to the page you requested.  The text shown in red is the active link.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
(1449, 'add new', 'Create an item.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
(1450, 'added', 'Has been included, appended, or increased.', '', 'tv', '', 1, 'core'),
