(1945, 'namespace', 'A zone of a directory or file structure in which names must be unique.', '"Namespace" is a difficult concept to define, but it is easy to describe.  Imagine you have a file that you call "important.txt", which store in a directory called "My Documents".  Now, imagine you create another file, with other information, and you also want to call it "important.txt".  You can either:\r\na) save the new file with the name "important.txt" in any directory *except* "My Documents"\r\nb) save the new file in the "My Documents" directory with a *different name*\r\nc) *replace* the original file with the new file.\r\n\r\nThe one thing you *cannot* do is have two files in the same directory with the same name; you cannot have two files in the "My Documents" directory that are both named "important.txt".\r\n\r\nSo, the "My Documents" directory is a namespace - it is a zone where each file must have a different name from every other file in the same zone.', 'n', '', 1, 'core'),
